## Impact of Nursing-Based Outcome Studies Led by APRNs

The evidence supports that nursing-based outcome studies led or encouraged by APRNs result in:

| Outcome Area                  | Impact of APRN-Led Outcome Studies                         | References                                      |
|------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| Patient Satisfaction          | Improved satisfaction scores and patient-reported outcomes | Dubree et al., 2015; Newhouse et al., 2011     |
| Clinical Outcomes            | Better management of chronic diseases and reduced hospitalizations | Dubree et al., 2015                            |
| Cost-Effectiveness            | Significant cost savings and cost avoidance                 | Paez & Allen, 2006; Newhouse et al., 2011      |
| Job Satisfaction             | Higher APRN job satisfaction and retention                  | Dubree et al., 2015                             |
| Nursing Practice Development | Enhanced nursing knowledge and evidence-based practice culture | Leske, 2007; Waterman et al., 2007              |

---

## Conclusion

APRNs are essential drivers of nursing-based outcome studies. Through integrating evidence-based practice, utilizing structured frameworks, leading research initiatives, developing measurement competencies, fostering collaborative practice, addressing barriers, and disseminating findings, APRNs can significantly encourage and enhance nursing research. This, in turn, leads to improved patient outcomes, cost-effective care, and professional advancement in nursing.

Healthcare organizations and nursing leaders should support APRNs by providing resources, education, and institutional backing to maximize their role in outcome studies. The growing body of evidence underscores the value of APRN-led outcome research in transforming healthcare delivery and advancing nursing science.

